    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p>Not published before <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>120400</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <persName type="divine" ref="#Hermes"><name nymRef="#Ἑρμῆς"><unclear>Ἑ</unclear>ρμε<supplied reason="lost">ῖ</supplied></name></persName> 
                        <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> à Hermès <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> for Hermes <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> per Hermes <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p>[---] لأجل هيرميس [---]</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>The name of Hermes at the dative case (and in koine form) is a clue for a dedication in the gymnasium, which was still at the time located where 
                the Caesareum later stood. The name of Heracles possibly stood in the lost part, as both deities are usually mentioned together as protectors of 
                the gymnasium.</p>
	       <p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
